			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				Anonymous Ranger,<BR>
Thanks for such a realistic and balanced evaluation.  Bards do NOT do what rangers do, nearly so well, nor what warrior do, so well, or enchanters, or thieves, or wizards, shamans, etc.<BR>
<BR>
Every bard who knows what they are doing recongizes this, and adapts to this situation to fit the groups weakness, or solos.<BR>
<BR>
What we do, when we do it well (I was stunned to be grouped at two different times tonight with 2 bards at lvl 22 and 23 who *boggle* DIDNT know how to twist, and wouldnt try it. *sigh* - I showed them how and got them on the path) is to add to a groups strengths or help patch up its weaknesses.<BR>
<BR>
My reply below to the Ranger/ Track issue was to Rangerboy anon, who basically said &quot;bards suck, you cant track and I can ha ha ha&quot; well we can track, but like I said, we arent rangers.<BR>
<BR>
I hope you have grouped with a good bard, and seen what one can do.  There are a lot of twinked crappy bards out there, and they make it hard for the rest of us, except when we are wanted as a manabattery only, and then most bards, myself anyway, refuse to play manasong all the time, unless the caster needs the mana for a heal or whatever.<BR>
<BR>
Why play manasong when with my drum everyone in the group gets +8 to ac, +26 to Dex, and +26 to str, as well as my slowing the mob and reducing its AC, and me buffing the group with + 38 disease resist, +38 Magic resist, +38 poison resist (to name one of our rhythm buffs) and hitting the mob for melee damage as  well?<BR>
<BR>
Ahh, bards, either you hate em or you get a good one and you learn what they can do.<BR>
<BR>
Gileas Dreamsinger, MM server, bard of the 35th string
				</font>
			</td>

